1470","1490":"1490","1459":"1459","1447":"1447","1535":"1535","1502":"1502","1524":"1524","1523":"1523","1488":"1488","1466":"1466","1542":"1542","1443":"1443","1553":"1553","1463":"1463","Aft 1490":"after 1490","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","St Martins in The Fields, London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Wakefield, West Yorkshire, England":"Wakefield, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Arksey, Yorkshire, England":"Arksey, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bradford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places, large and small, called Bradford; in particular the city in Yorkshire, which originally rose to prosperity as a wool town. There are others in Derbyshire, Devon, Dorset, Greater Manchester, Norfolk, Somerset, Cheshire, Wiltshire and elsewhere. They are all named with Old English <i>brād</i> ‘broad’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","History: This name was brought independently to North American by many different bearers from the 17th century onward. William Bradford (1590–1657), born in Austerfield in South Yorkshire, England, the son of a yeoman farmer, was among the Pilgrim Fathers who emigrated to North America on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620. He was a signer of the Mayflower Compact and in 1621 he was elected governor of Plymouth colony, being re-elected thirty times. Another William Bradford (1663–1752), printer, came from Barnwell, Leicestershire, England, to Philadelphia, PA, in 1685, subsequently moving to New York, where he set up a printing press and founded a paper mill. His grandson, also called William Bradford (1721–91), was known as ‘the patriot printer’, famous for his Philadelphia newspaper, which among other things denounced the Stamp Act, \"which no American can mention without abhorrence\"."],"variants":[{"name":"Braford","meanings":["English: variant of   Bradford  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Brafford","meanings":["English: variant of   Bradford  . This surname has now died out in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Constance","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval form of the Late Latin name <i>Constantia</i>, which is either a feminine derivative of <i>Constans</i> (  see  Constant  ) or an abstract noun meaning ‘constancy’. This was a popular name among the Normans, and was borne by, amongst others, the formidable Constance of Sicily (  1158–98 ), wife of the Emperor  Henry VI ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Constance Bradford was born in 1470, in Wakefield, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Jasper Bradford, was 27 and her mother, Margaret Ogle, was 23. She married Robert Rotherforth in 1488, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1490, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1470–Aft 1490":"1470–pärast 1490","1462–1463":"1462–1463","1466–1524":"1466–1524","1470–1490":"1470–1490","1473–1553":"1473–1553","1460–1502":"1460–1502","1490–1523":"1490–1523","1443–1535":"1443–1535","1447–1542":"1447–1542","1473":"1473","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1459":"1459","1447":"1447","1535":"1535","1502":"1502","1524":"1524","1523":"1523","1488":"1488","1466":"1466","1542":"1542","1443":"1443","1553":"1553","1463":"1463","Aft 1490":"pärast 1490","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","St Martins in The Fields, London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wakefield, West Yorkshire, England":"Wakefield, West Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Arksey, Yorkshire, England":"Arksey, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1470–Aft 1490":"1470–1490 jälkeen","1462–1463":"1462–1463","1466–1524":"1466–1524","1470–1490":"1470–1490","1473–1553":"1473–1553","1460–1502